SKILL|obliteratus|"OBLITERATUS: abliterate LLM refusals (diff-in-means)."
STEP|1|CLI methods, 28 analysis modules, 116 model presets across 5 compute tiers, tournament evaluation, and telemetry-driven recommendations.
STEP|2|License warning:** OBLITERATUS is AGPL-3.0. NEVER import it as a Python library. Always invoke via CLI (`obliteratus` command) or subprocess. This keeps Hermes Agent's MIT license clean.
STEP|3|Wants to "uncensor" or "abliterate" an LLM
STEP|4|Asks about removing refusal/guardrails from a model
STEP|5|Wants to create an uncensored version of Llama, Qwen, Mistral, etc.
STEP|6|Mentions "refusal removal", "abliteration", "weight projection"
STEP|7|Wants to analyze how a model's refusal mechanism works
STEP|8|References OBLITERATUS, abliterator, or refusal directions
STEP|9|IMPORTANT:** Confirm with user before installing. This pulls in ~5-10GB of dependencies (PyTorch, Transformers, bitsandbytes, etc.).
STEP|10|Default / recommended for most cases: `advanced`.** It uses multi-direction SVD with norm-preserving projection and is well-tested.
STEP|11|**basic** — Single refusal direction via diff-in-means. Fast (~5-10 min for 8B).
STEP|12|**advanced** (DEFAULT, RECOMMENDED) — Multiple SVD directions, norm-preserving projection, 2 refinement passes. Medium speed (~10-20 min).
STEP|13|**aggressive** — Whitened SVD + jailbreak-contrastive + attention head surgery. Higher risk of coherence damage.
STEP|14|**spectral_cascade** — DCT frequency-domain decomposition. Research/novel approach.
STEP|15|**informed** — Runs analysis DURING abliteration to auto-configure. Experimental — slower and less predictable than advanced.
STEP|16|**surgical** — SAE features + neuron masking + head surgery + per-expert. Very slow (~1-2 hrs). Best for reasoning models.
STEP|17|**optimized** — Bayesian hyperparameter search (Optuna TPE). Longest runtime but finds optimal parameters.
STEP|18|**inverted** — Flips the refusal direction. Model becomes actively willing.
STEP|19|**nuclear** — Maximum force combo for stubborn MoE models. Expert-granular.
STEP|20|**diff_means** (default) — Simple difference-in-means between refused/complied activations. Robust.
STEP|21|**svd** — Multi-direction SVD extraction. Better for complex alignment.
STEP|22|**leace** — LEACE (Linear Erasure via Closed-form Estimation). Optimal linear erasure.
STEP|23|failspy, gabliteration, heretic, rdo
STEP|24|Try `aggressive` method
STEP|25|Increase `--n-directions` (e.g., 8 or 16)
STEP|26|Add `--refinement-passes 3`
STEP|27|Try `--direction-method svd` instead of diff_means
STEP|28|Reduce `--n-directions` (try 2)
STEP|29|Increase `--regularization` (try 0.3)
STEP|30|Reduce `--refinement-passes` to 1
STEP|31|Try `basic` method (gentler)
STEP|32|**Embedding Ablation** — Target embedding layer components
STEP|33|**FFN Ablation** — Feed-forward network block removal
STEP|34|**Head Pruning** — Attention head pruning
STEP|35|**Layer Removal** — Full layer removal
STEP|36|Refusal rate benchmarking
STEP|37|Perplexity comparison (before/after)
STEP|38|LM Eval Harness integration for academic benchmarks
STEP|39|Head-to-head competitor comparison
STEP|40|Baseline performance tracking
STEP|41|**CUDA** — Full support (NVIDIA GPUs)
STEP|42|**Apple Silicon (MLX)** — Supported via MLX backend
STEP|43|**CPU** — Supported for tiny models (< 1B params)
STEP|44|`templates/abliteration-config.yaml` — Standard single-model config
STEP|45|`templates/analysis-study.yaml` — Pre-abliteration analysis study
STEP|46|`templates/batch-abliteration.yaml` — Multi-model batch processing
STEP|47|**Don't use `informed` as default** — it's experimental and slower. Use `advanced` for reliable results.
STEP|48|**Models under ~1B respond poorly to abliteration** — their refusal behaviors are shallow and fragmented, making clean direction extraction difficult. Expect partial results (20-40% remaining refusal)
STEP|49|**`aggressive` can make things worse** — on small models it can damage coherence and actually increase refusal rate. Only use it if `advanced` leaves > 10% refusals on a 3B+ model.
STEP|50|**Always check perplexity** — if it spikes > 15%, the model is damaged. Reduce aggressiveness.
STEP|51|**MoE models need special handling** — use `nuclear` method for Mixtral, DeepSeek-MoE, etc.
STEP|52|**Quantized models can't be re-quantized** — abliterate the full-precision model, then quantize the output.
STEP|53|**VRAM estimation is approximate** — 4-bit quant helps but peak usage can spike during extraction.
STEP|54|**Reasoning models are sensitive** — use `surgical` for R1 distills to preserve chain-of-thought.
STEP|55|**Check `obliteratus recommend`** — telemetry data may have better parameters than defaults.
STEP|56|**AGPL license** — never `import obliteratus` in MIT/Apache projects. CLI invocation only.
STEP|57|**Large models (70B+)** — always use `--large-model` flag for conservative defaults.
STEP|58|**Spectral certification RED is common** — the spectral check often flags "incomplete" even when practical refusal rate is 0%. Check actual refusal rate rather than relying on spectral certification a
STEP|59|**vllm** — Serve abliterated models with high throughput
STEP|60|**gguf** — Convert abliterated models to GGUF for llama.cpp
STEP|61|**huggingface-tokenizers** — Work with model tokenizers
